Hungarian policy, and Hungarian authorities committed mass robbery, deportations, and killings against all non-Magyar groups in their efforts to recast the region as part of an ethnonational "Greater Hungary." In considering the events that preceded the German invasion of Hungary in March 1944, this book reorients our view of the Holocaust not simply as a German drive for continent-wide genocide, but as a truly international campaign of mass murder, related to violence against non-Jews unleashed by projects of state and nation building. Focusing on both state and society, Raz Segal shows how Hungary's genocidal attack on Subcarpathian Rus' obliterated not only tens of thousands of lives but also a diverse society and way of life that today, from the vantage point of our world of nation-states, we find difficult to imagine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aGenocidezRuthenia (Czechoslovakia)xHistoryy20th century. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zRuthenia (Czechoslovakia). 0aState-sponsored terrorismzHungaryxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAtrocitieszRuthenia (Czechoslovakia). 4aCarpatho-Ruthenians. 4aHolocaust. 4aHungary. 4aJews. 4aSubcarpathian Rus'. 4aWorld War II. 4aantisemitism. 4agenocide. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804798976zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798976423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804798976.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles